IRRADIATION OF FOODSTUFFS: A SUGGESTION (03)
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
[see
Irradiation of foodstuffs: a suggestion 970903121521
Irradiation of foodstuffs: a suggestion (02) 970904123753]
[1]
Date: Wed, 3 Sep 1997 16:11:09 EST
From: Kenneth N. Hall <KHALL@canr1.cag.uconn.edu>
I have been under the impression that the dose of irradiation needed to kill
gets greater as the form of life gets smaller, i.e., less irradiation is
needed to kill parasites than bacteria and less to kill bacteria than
viruses. I am also of the opinion that the amount of irradiation currently
permitted for use on foods is not adequate to destroy viruses. I suspect
that prions would require even greater amounts of irradiation than needed for
destruction of viruses, but have not read on this topic.
We need not over simplify the issue [by saying] that irradiation will make
the food absolutely sterile or safe.
---
Kenneth N. Hall, Ph.D.
Professor, Department of Nutritional Sciences
University of Connecticut
Storrs, CT 06269-4017
